Linux and MAC users

To use the Qulog emacs mode, assuming you have a site-lisp directory, add qulog.el to that directory.

To your .emacs file (or Preferences file if using aquamacs) add

(autoload 'qulog-mode "qulog" "Major mode for editing Qulog programs." t)
(setq auto-mode-alist (cons '("\\.qlg$" . qulog-mode) auto-mode-alist))


Windows Users running emacs for Windows

Assuming you have installed emacs for Windows then follow the following steps
(for the user named auser)

1. In system/advanced settings/Environment variables add the following
    HOME   c:\users\auser
    PATH   ;c:\emacs\bin  (add to end of existing PATH variable - assuming
             emacs installed in c:\emacs\bin)

2. In c:\users\auser create the folder .emacs.d
   (and withing that folder add the folder lisp)

3. In c:\users\auser\.emacs.d create the file init.d and in that file
   add the following

(setq load-path (cons "c:/users/auser/.emacs.d/lisp" load-path)
(autoload 'qulog-mode "qulog" "Major mode for editing Qulog programs." t)
(setq auto-mode-alist (cons '("\\.qlg$" . qulog-mode) auto-mode-alist))


NOTE: load-path uses forward slashes

4. Add qulog.el to the c:/users/auser/.emacs.d/lisp folder

5. Log out and when you log back in and then if you start a Command Prompt
   and then cd to the folder containing, say qlexample.qlg, then
   emacs qlexample.qlg
   should start up emacs and use the syntax highlighting and indentation
   for Qulog/Teleor